<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-543-585  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 543 585.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Oct 16 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Byte magazine available to Russians.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Tchashchin, Kirill.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   McGraw-Hill Inc. (marketing).andO;Ticker:    MHP.andO;Topic:     InformatikaMarketing StrategyMagazinesDistribution ManagementByte (Periodical)Soviet UnionComputer industry.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>BYTE MAGAZINE AVAILABLE TO RUSSIANS MOSCOW, U.S.S.R., 1990 OCT 16 (NB) --McGraw-Hill representatives are selling Byte magazine at the Informatika-90show in Moscow and they are accepting subscriptions as well.andP;  All magazineand subscription sales are being handled in roubles.andM;Representatives of the company's British branch are offering single issuesand yearly subscriptions to both Byte and Business Week International to allshow participants.andP;  This is the first opportunity for people in the USSR toget these magazines for roubles although prices were set too high formagazine to become available for general distribution.andM;A single issue of Byte is selling for 40 roubles while a one-yearsubscription is 1,000 roubles in cash.andP;  The price is simply the regular $50surface mail price multiplied by 20 -- the market rouble to dollar exchangerate.andP;  Business Week is priced at 20 roubles per issue -- expensive comparedwith the Economist and Time which are available at newsstands for 3 roubleseach.andM;Representative of McGraw Hill told Newsbytes that the publishing house hasentered into an agreement with one bank which has agreed to accept a roubledeposit to be converted into dollars at the firstin the first officialoccasion on the future.andM;&quot;Unfortunately, even a well-paid Soviet programmer can't afford tosubscribe,&quot; Mr. Dimitry Mozhaev of Vega, a small company, told Newsbytes.andM;(Kirill Tchashchin/19901013)</TEXT></DOC>